:INFO
Cider Problems and Fixes
Most cider problems have one of three causes: poor sanitization, wrong temperature, or preservatives in the juice. This page covers the most common issues.

:PATH
Fermentation Never Started
Check for preservatives in the juice and verify yeast is viable.
|
:INFO
Fermentation Never Started
If the airlock shows no activity after 48 hours, check three things. First: did you use juice with potassium sorbate or sodium benzoate? Both prevent fermentation. Second: was your yeast expired or stored improperly? Proof it in warm water with a pinch of sugar first. Third: is the airlock actually sealed? Sometimes bubbles escape around the stopper without passing through the airlock.

:PATH
Cider Tastes Like Vinegar
Acetic acid bacteria got in — likely from poor sanitization.
|
:INFO
Cider Tastes Like Vinegar
Vinegar flavor means acetic acid bacteria contaminated the batch. This usually enters through unsanitized equipment or an airlock that ran dry — exposing the cider to air. Once vinegar character is present the batch cannot be fixed for drinking, but it makes excellent apple cider vinegar. Use it as such and sanitize more thoroughly next time.

:PATH
Cider Is Too Dry and Tart
Fermentation consumed all sugar — back-sweeten before bottling.
|
:INFO
Cider Is Too Dry and Tart
Dry cider with no residual sweetness is correct for wine-style cider. To sweeten without refermentation: first stabilize with potassium sorbate, then add honey, apple juice concentrate, or sugar to taste. Wait 48 hours to confirm no renewed fermentation before bottling. Alternatively, blend with fresh juice at serving time.

:NOTE
Off-Flavors Usually Come from One Place
Sulfur smell in early fermentation is normal and dissipates. Nail polish remover smell is ethyl acetate from yeast stress — often too warm or too little nutrients. Band-aid or medicinal flavor comes from chlorophenols: use filtered water for any additions and avoid bleach to sanitize equipment.
